{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930110201/0397.xml":{"full_text":"A-4\nWALSH WINES\nFIGHT WITH FAITH\nPersonality of Montanan Is\nBig Factor in Consideration\nof .Any Voter.\nBY WILLIAM HARD.,\nNow is the tUpe tq wrjte about \u25a0'Torn\"\nWalsh. ,of Montana, before he. gets\nturned. Into a \"lame, d,uck\" by his Re\npublican senatorial adversary in Mon\ntana. \u2018JUdge Albert J. Galen, as the Re\npublican? &ay lie will b\u2019 the\nDemocrats and the. mass of political\nprognosticators \u00a7ay emphatically he will\nnot be. The prognosticators, sgme of\nthem,. jhlnk that \u201cTom,\u201d though dry,,\nhas saved himself from being sent up\nSalt Creek as a I\u2019Jame duck\u201d by becom\ning sufficiently web-footed in th; waters\nof immediate politics to swim toward a\nbelief.\".in .the propriety of re.ferendums\non wet waves. Others, subtler ans\ndeeper, hold that it is unreasonable to\nthink that a voter could look at \"Tom\"\nand ridl send him and re-re-send him\nto the Senate\u2014or to some station still\nloftier, if Imaginable.\nAbsurd to Call Him \"Tom.\"\nIt is .-absurd that he should be. called\n\u201cTom.\u201d One might as well have called\nWilliam Ewart Gladstone \"Bill\" or\u2014\nsaving the Irreverence St. Peter\nPete.'\u2019* Mr. Walsh, indeed, in any\nproperly cast and thoroughly reverent\nmiracle plav would make an admirable\nSt. Peter. He would hold the keys of\nHeaven with an air dhich would need\nno artificial effort to indicate to all be\nholders' that exact- justice was going to\nbe done with a precision laborious, con\nsld-rate, sensitive and implacable.\nShort of the post at the Pearly Oates,\nthere Is nothing really entirely befitting\nMr. Walsh except a seat in the Supreme\nCourt.. Whatever levity may now ap\npear among the..venerable practitioners\nbefore that venerable trtbunal would\nthereupon be thoroughly hushed His\nfellow-justices might have perception\nenough to call him \"Thomas,\" There\nwas no perception, just the same, in\nwhoever it was that christened him\nafter the doubting apostle.\nHas Both Fight and Faith.\nThomas J. Walsh does not doubt. He\ndoes not doubt religion. He does not\ndoubt righteousness. He does not doubt\nthe validity.ef good. ,He does not doubt\nthe possibility ,of the arrival at good.\nHe is among the very few men in public\nlife who seem never to be penetrated by\neven a sliver of cynicism. S\u2019rious\nthough he is. he accordingly seems\nnever genuinely depressed or disheart\nened. In the midst of his seriousness,\nwhich *s really portentous, he seems\nalso continuously actually cheerful. Be\nlieving in God and His world, he is op\npressed'by duty but at the same time\nsustainid by-serenity. He has fight, but\nhe also has faith.\nHe thus acquires In Washington a\naort of,awe at his dignity but also a\nsort of tendemesa toward the spirit\nuality that is in him. Severe as he\nhas been toward national culprits in\nthe Republican party, he has many Re\npublican friends and is much invited\nto Republican houses. He very fre\nquently accepts the invitations.\nIs Austere Though Sociable.\nAustere throughout the whole day.\nIncluding the evening, he is neverthe\nless. in the evening, and in his way,\nsociable. That is, he likes to be in,\nthe same room w-ith other people and\nseems to like the. people\nthemselves. He will not, drink with\nthem. He wily nbt 'snloke with them.\nHe wlB not even cosume tea or coffee\nwith them. He is in such matters\na complete asset**-- He -never sermon\nises for jwceticlsm. He simply quietly\npractices it. His conviviality in the eve\nning BTKat In the middle of dinner he\nwill follow up some remark of some\nbody\u2019s by saying \"now let\u2019s look into\nthat!\" and~hs will thereupon descend\ninto it as into a well, and presently be\nengaged in excavating the jurassic and\ntriassic strata and substrata of it\ndown through all geological depths to\noriginal creative infinity. He thus has\na good time, and so does everybody else,\nexcept the unfortunate person who made\na remark about the grass without re\nflecting upon the Jurassic and triassic\neras underneath.\nSpirit Transcends Creed.\nHe could be an extremely forbidding\ncharacter if he were In temperament\nmaterialistic. He has a- mind like a\npneumatic drill and a steam dredge.\nHe is rescued from being a mere mon\nstrous mauling mechanism by having\nalso a true life of the spirit. It ob\nviously transcends creed.. His Cathol\nicism has not impeded numerous meet\nings of Protestant clergymen in this\ncampaign in Montana from giving him\ntheir open indorsement. He is in truth,\nit might adventurously be said, a per\nson of Catholic religion but of Protes\ntant reformists views. He favors pro\nhibition. He favors the World Court and\nthe League of Nations. The general\nsupport for those projects in this coun\ntry is dominantly protestant, and dom\ninantly ecclesiastically protestant, Mr.\nWalsh is in his personal habits a sort\nof Catholic Puritan and in his public\npolicies a sort of Catholic Methodist\nor Baptist.\nSuch considerations, however, remain\nsecondary in hia political prospects.'\nThe primary influence on his behalf\nnext Tuesday at the polls in Montana\nwill be the striking resemblance which\nso many of his fellow citizens think\nthey see between him and the proper\nqualifications for any high office, ir\nrespective of religion, irrespective of\nparty, irrespective of platform, irres\npective of anything except what is il\nlustrated by the feeling that brash and\nuppish Senators who call him \u201cTom'\u2019\nought to call him \"Thomas\u201d and \"sir.\"\n5 Rooms and Bath\n$63\u2014575\nSAVOY\n2804 14th Street\n5%\nInterest on Savings\nSemi-Annually\nCompounded\nU. S. TREASURY SUPERVISION\nCOLUMBIA PERMANENT\nBUILDING ASSOCIATION\n733 12th St. N.W.\nSubscribe Today\nIt costs only about 1H cents\nper day and 5 cent* Sundays to\nhave Washington\u2019s best newspa\nper delivered to you regularly\nevery evening and Sunday morn\ning.\nTelephone National 5000 and\nthe delivery -Till start immedi\nately. The Route Agent will col\nlect at the .-nd of each month.\na \u2014s\u25a0 i nmi i 11 1 I\nTRAIN WRECK IN WHICH TWO WERE KILLED\nWreck of a Baltimore Ohio express train near Ream eysville, W. Va., in which the fireman and engineer were\nkilled. The train, hound from Washington to Pittsburgh, was being detoured over a temporary track when it was wrecked.\nIssues of the Campaign\nRepublicans Say Foes\nHare Stood on Tariff\nRepeal Alone\n(Continued From First Page!\nregarded the tariff with genuine satis-\nfaction. They cried with assumed hor\nror that it would cost the country a j\nbillion dollars a year, yet they have j\nnever singled out a single rate that they\ncould show or even claimed was too j\nhigh. When that fake was exploded j\nthey took another tact, declaring with\ndile solemnity that foreign nations j\nwould punish us for daring to preserve\nthe American market for the American\nfarmer and American workman. When I\nthat ingenuous myth failed to panic J\nthe country, the tariff as an after din-\nner subject lost its appeal.\nRenewed Their Attack.\nThe Democrats then renewed their\nattack upon the President and the ad\nministration, seeking in the absence of\nreal issues to convince the electorate j\nthat the President was responsible for\nthe business depression, the stock mar\nket crash, the drought and the South\nAmerican revolutions.\nUndoubtedly the Democrats regard\nthe business depression as the greatest\nblessing to which their party has fallen\nheir in many a long year. It is not,\nhowever, an issue between the two\nparties in this election. Both parties\nare agreed that everything possible\nshould be done td banish it and restore\nprosperity. The only difference being\nthat whereas the Republican party is\ndoing everything possible to counteract\nthe effects of world-wide economic dis\ntress, the Democratic party has not\nmade a single effort to ameliorate con\nditions.\nThe Raskob subsidized attempt to\n\"smear\u201d Hoover also has become an is\nsue in this campaign. The libelous\nand dispicable attacks upon the Presi\ndent, which emanated from this bureau,\nhave .been, checked because of the wide\nspread public indignation over the I\ncountry when the facts became known, j\nOne Clear-Cut Issue.\nLacking any constructive program\nwith which to appeal to the voters, the\nDemocrats have thus been compelled\nthroughout the campaign to rely on\nsmoke screens, myths and libels. De- j\nprived of these artifices one by one.\nthey come to election day with but one\nclear-cut issue\u2014the tariff.\nThey stand ready to repeal the tariff, j\nto subject the country to another long j\nperiod of uncertainty and business dis- j\ntress until the day when their \"protec- I\ntion for revenue only\" tariff throws\nopen the American market to the world I\nand forces the American farmer and i\nworkingman to compete with the pauper\nfanners and laborers of foreign coun\ntries.\nHarbors 12.000 Mice.\nRAYLEIGH, England (A s ).\u2014Caring\nfor 20,000 mice is the business here of\nWillie Tuck, who furnishes scores of\nEuropean laboratories \u201cwith rodents for\nexperimental purposes.\nI\ngggsl V F v the avenue I _\ngg%|| AT SEVENTH\nII I I MONDAY is the last day! h\nAny man ivho needs a Suit\nor Overcoat will save now!\nr J' HESE are not A 'W' \u2019W 1\nordinary clothes, I M\nand these are not or-\ndinarv savings! To\na brilliant apecial OF HIGHER-PRICED\npurchase of Suit*\nand Overcoats from r pT) T T3\nour regular makers, U U C i\\\nwe have added out- M vX/ffa i\nH standing selections SvjlTo AND\nV/yVyfy from our own\nI\u25a0\u25a0 higher-priced stock. O\\7TsU A HPO\nAll at the one sale V i>iVV'Wr\\. 1 U\nEVERYTHING ||P\nnew and correct.\nIn Suits smart r H\nmodels and patterns JW H\nin Greys, Browns I\nand Mixed Blues. I\nIn Overcoats\u2014fine I\nBoucles, Llamas and iH\nMrllnnt Blurt,\nTHE SUNDAY STAR. WASHINGTON. D. C, Non EMBER 2, 1930\u2014PART ONE.\nDemocrats to Rest Their\nCase on Success or\nFailure of Hoover.\n(Continued From First Page\npended on his election. As elements of\nthis pledge and details of the prescrip\ntion for its accomplishment were such\nitems as a tariff that should place\nagriculture on a par with industry in\nthe distribution of tariff favors, and a\nprogram of farm relief that should re\nstore the business of agriculture to a\nflourishing condition.\nNo Limits Attached.\nThere were no limitations attached\nto these promises. If the country re\nturned a Republican administration the\nsun would continue to shine on our\nbusiness and the farm' industry would\nparticipate in the warmth. If the\nDemocrats won there would be an in\nterruption to the era of success. On\ni the extent of which the campaign com\nmitments were realized the administra\ntion is to be judged.\nTherefore the Hoover administration\nis the real, all-including issue of the\ncampaign. Subsidiary to that is the\nvalue or detriment of the so-called\nGrundy tariff and the farm relief pro-\nI gram. If the first conduces to the\nrestoration of the prosperity that has\nfailed us the Republicans must gain;\nif. on the contrary, it has resulted in\nretaliatory tariffs that have caused the\ndestruction of our import business, the\nRepublican party must answer for the\ndisaster. Similarly if Mr. Hoover\u2019s farm\nrelief system has helped the farmer,\nhis party should reap the benefits; if,\non the other hand it has failed to pro\nduce living prices for farm products that\nparty must accept the responsibility.\nProhibition No Issue.\nThese then are the national ques\ntions that must be decided on Tuesday,\nj Prohibition, though a vital factor in\nmany States is not such a national is\nsue in this election. The candidates of\nboth parties are wet or dry according\nto the sentiment, determined or pre\nsumed, in the different sections of the\ncountry. Until the national conventions\ni take a definite stand that question must\nremain a local issue. There being no\nnational utterance on the subject in\nthe present campaign, for the obvious\nreason that there exists no body that\ncan speak with authority for either\nj party, on the maintenance or repeal of\nthe eighteenth amendment and the Vol\ni stead law. that question, though of the\ni utmost importance in the political for-\nI tunes of individual candidates, cannot\nbe considered a party matter.\nRuss Dirigible in Prospect.\nMOSCOW OP).\u2014Following a visit of\nthe Graf Zeppelin to Moscow the news\npaper Pravda, official organ of the Com\nmunist patty, has started subscriptions\nto a fund with which to build a Rus\nsian dirigible.\nRASKOBDENOUNCES\nPOSIERS OF G. 0. P.\nDemocrat Denies Implication\nThat He Sold Short With\nMarket Depression.\nJohn J. Raskob, chairman of the\nDemocratic National Committee. Issued\na vigorous denunciation yesterday of\nthe advertising poster which has been\nj circulated by the Republican National\nCommittee, quoting from an Interview\nI h\u00ab gave the Ladies\u2019 Home Journal, In\nAugust, 1929, suggesting investments in\ncommon stocks as a road to wealth.\nThe poster carried at its top\na streamer, printed in type an Inch\nhigh, asking: \u201cWho Caused the Stock\nMarket Crash?\u201d Beside the interview\nwith Mr. Raskob was reproduced a\nnewspaper article, published in March,\n1929. in which Andrew W. Mellon. Sec\nretary of the Treasury, urged the\npublic to invest in conservative bonds,\nwhich might prove less profitable im\nmediately, but were safer.\n\"My attention has been called to a\nposter or advertisement issued by the\nRepublican National Committee con\nveying the inference that I have by\nshort selling in the market deliberately\nInfluenced the depression of the mar\nket,\" Mr. Raskob said in a statement\nIssued through the Democratic Na\ntional Committee, \"I wish to notify the\nnewspapers of the United States that I\nregard this as a libelous utterance and\nmust hold any agency that publishes it\nresponsible. The Inference Is carried\nin large type, in which the question is\nput. Did Raskob Sell Short?\u2019 The\njuxtaposition of headlines conveys an\naffirmative answer to the pernicious\nquery.\n\"As a matter of fact, not only did 1\nnot sell short in the market that suf\nfered a collapse after almost every op\ntimistic prophecy by President Hoover\nand his executive departments, but\nnever at any time since the advent of\nthe present administration, which, of\ni course, embraces the whole of the\nHoover panic from the crash of a year\nago to this hour, did I either personally\nor through agents, either directly ot in\ndirectly, sell short even a single share\nof stock or any commodity.\n\u201cI am moved to issue this warning\n1 because the charge transcends the limi\ntations of politics and is a direct as\nsault of my business integrity and\nintelligence.\u201d\nHOLD HALLOWEEN PARTY\nThree Prizes Awarded at Noel\nHouse Friday Night.\nAn old-fashioned Halloween party\nwas held at the Noel House Friday\nnight.\nThree prizes were given for costumes.\nFirst to Ernest Stasulli of the junior\ni class, the second to Jimmy Cook of the\nintermediate class and third to Harry\nMeyers of the seniors.\nELECTION FINANCE\nREPORTS ARE MADE\n$25,000 Contribution From\nMellon Heads'List of Re\npublican Gifts.\nA check for $25,000 from Andrew\nW. Mellon. Secretary of the Treasury,\nand his brother. R. B. Mellon, of Pitts\nburgh. topped the final pre-election list\nof Republican campaign contributors\nfiled yesterday with the clerk of the\nHouse of Representatives by the Repub\nlican National Committee.\nThe report, signed by Joseph R. Nutt, j\ntreasurer of the committee, covered the\nbrief period from October 21 to October\n30. It listed contributions received dur\ning that period totaling $103,575, with\na grand total since January 1 of $548,-\n616. To this was added a surplus of\n$136,363.38 left over from 1929.\nDisbursements since January 1 aggre\ngated $678,056.11, leaving a balance of\n$6,923.27 on hand on the eve of one of\nthe hardest-contested off-year congres\nsional campaigns in the history of\nAmerican politics. During the period\nfrom October 21 to October 30 the\ncommittee paid out $104,695, most of\nwhich was sent to a few States where\nthe election battle is hottest.\n$10,085 Gifts Reported.\nThe Democratic National Committee\nreported campaign contributions aggre\ngating $10,085 for the period from Oc\ntober 23 to October 29. Robert E.\nGreenwood of Fitchburg, con\ntributed the SIO,OOO. The remaining\nSBS came from unnamed miscellaneous\nsources. Together with a balance of\n$13,673.85 on hand, the Democratic\ncampaign chest at the time the report\nwas filed represented $23,758.85. Out\nof this disbursements totaling $11,154.53\nwere reported, leaving a balance of\n$12,604.32 on hand.\nJames W. Gerard, the Democratic\nnational treasurer, listed several in\nteresting \u201cliabilities,\u201d however. One\nwas a debt of $375,000 with interest\ndue the Bankers\u2019 Trust Co. of New\nYork. The other was the $220,000 ad\nvanced by John J. Raskob, Democratic\nnational chairman. It was listed as\n\"borrowed from Mr. Raskob.\u201d An un\npaid balance of $9,217.05 due Frank\nKierman Co.. New York advertising\nfirm, also was listed.\nThe \"Prohibition National Commit\ntee'\u2019 (loyal section) also reported. By\nway of explaining the words \"loyal\nsection,\u201d in parenthesis, Will D. Martin\nof New Jersey, treasurer, pointed out\nthat officials of the original committee\nhad bolted and supported the Repub\nlican candidates. The committee there\nupon was reorganized without them,\nMr. Martin said. He reported $1,020 in\ncontributions and disburaements total\ning $913.64.\nSome of the outstanding contribu\ntioas to the Republican campaign\nfollow:\nGeorge Woodruff. Chicago, $10,000;\nFrank J. Thiel, Washington: Vincent\nBendlx, Chicago; Edward F. Hutton,\nNew York; Senator Hamilton F. Kean,\nThe Terms of Morris Plan Loans\nAre Simple and Practical\nIt is not Necessary to Have Had\nan Account at this Bank to Borrow\nor $l2O EASY TO PAY Loan* are passed\nborrowed you within a day or\nagree to deposit O,w,T tvvo after filing\n$lO a month for toria application\n12 months in an Lo\u00ab\u00bb Monthi w jth f ew *xcep\naccount, the pro- sl\u00a3o SIO.OO tions.\nceeds of which SI6Q s qq\nmay be used to J-TT f.rJ-rr j\ncancel the note i 240 520.00 MORRIS PLAN\nwhen due. De- S3OO $25.00 notes arc usually\nposits may be $360 $30.00 made for 1 year,\nmadeon a weekly $540 $45 00 though they may\nsemi-monthly or OAr nA 'nn be given for any\nmonthly basis as 53,200 SIOO.OO period of from 3\nmJ Vou prefer. $6,000 $500.00 to 12 months. Imm\nMORRIS PLAN BANK\nUnder Supervision of U. S. Treasury\n1408 H Street, N.W. Washington, D. C.\n\"Character and Earning Power Are the Basis of Credit\"\nI 3\nB:\u2014 M,\nLots of it\u2014\nAlways Ready\nwith this\nmarvelous\n|pg| .y^Pittibui^\nP j\u00a3S WATER HEATER\nJ$ The Pittsburg Monarch\nSuperfine\n||i\u00bbiil\u00a7 It's priced so low and so easy to\nIPiSiOT fitly, you can certainly afford it. Light\nit the day it arrives. You\u2019ll have con\nstant. evenly tempered hot water from\nthen on\u2014without the least attention.\nsM May we tell you all about it\u2014soon?\n19 510.00 Allowance for Your\nR gggfF Old Heater\nTWfr w T Convenient Terms\nEDGAR MORRIS SALES CO.\n1305 G St. N.W. NAtional 1031\nPittsburg Water Heaters Are Installed by Your Gas Go.\nor Your Plumber\ni\nDrugged?\nft' 't A\n.\u25a0L\ni JBaf-.;.\n\u2018T- k\n_ jiflL *v \\u(^r\nmarie McCarthy,\nEighteen, Wisconsin University co-ed,\nwho was fatally burned in a road house\nAre near Madison, Wis., wan drugged,\nher parents believe.\nNew Jersey, $6,000 each; J. M. More\nhead. New York. $3,300; George De\u00df.\nKeim, New Jersey; Senator David\nBaird, Jr., New Jersey; Ben R. Meyer.\nLos Angeles; George W. Hill, New\nYork; H. W. Croft, New York, and\nHarvey S. Firestone. Ohio, $2,500 each.\nFrederick M. Sackett, Ambassador to\nGermany; M. C. Migel, New York; F.\nW. Paine, Boston; E. S. Burke, jr.,\nCleveland; Alva Bradley, Cleveland,\n$2,000 each; Roger w. Straus, New\nYork; D. M. Cummings, Chicago; J. A.\nCampbell, Youngstown, Ohio; R. R. M.\nCarpenter, Wilmington, Del.; R. L. Pat\nterson, New York; Finley J. Shepard,\nNew' York; William Ziegler, jr., New\nYork; George Arents. jr\u201e New York,\nand Edgar Rickard, New York, SI,OOO\neach.\nRepublican Expenditures.\nDuring the 10 days covered by the\nreport, the Republican National Com\nmittee contributed to the Republican\nSenatorial Committee $12,900 and to\nthe Republican Congressional Commit\ntee $20,000. It also contributed to the\nfollowing State campaigns: Maryland,\n$4,000; New Hampshire, $2,000; Utah,\n$2,000; Kentucky, $6,500; Missouri,\n$6,000; Kansas, $1,500; Illinois, $5,000.\nIn addition, the National Committee\nspent, in the period covered, $6,000 in\nindividual congressional districts in\nNorth Carolina, divided as follows;\nTenth, $2,000; ninth, $2,000; seventh.\nSI,OOO, and fifth, SI,OOO. The report\noffered no explanation, of course. Com\nmittee officials explained outside, how\never, that these donations were sent to\nthe North Carolina districts to help\nRepublican candidates who are waging\nvigorous campaigns despite biased elec\ntion laws.\nThe Democratic Committee listed a\ni single donation to a State campaign.\nIt consisted of SIO,OOO, the exact\namount contributed by Mr. Greenwood\nof Massachusetts, which was sent to\nj help the campaign la the old Bay\n1 State.\nFather Fixes Baby\u2019s\nBudget for Month\nAt Total of $11.22\nJudge Multiplies Sum by\n4 and Grants Divorce\nto Young Wife.\n.'I\nBy th# Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, November I.\u2014Whet high\nschool graduate* know about the baby's\nbudget. Judge John J. Sullivan\ntoday, is not much.\nWilbur Coons, aged 28 and two years\nmarried, figured out a budget of $11.22\nper month for Wilbur, jr. Judge Bulr\nllvan doubled and redoubled him.\nAt the same time he granted a dhtorce\nto the mother, Mrs. Virginia Lee Cpons.\n17, who said her husband never btays\nwith her later than midnight befcause\nthe baby keeps him awake. This Is the\nbudget she said he submitted for- their\nbaby:\nMilk. $7.50.\nAlcohol. sl.l\u00df.\nSoap. 70 cents.\nVaseline, 10 cents.\nBottles, 25 cents.\nNipples, 15 cents.\nOlive oil, 29 cents.\nSoap flakes, 48 cents.\nTowels. 50 cents. 4\nTotal, $11.22 for the month.\nJudge Sullivan awarded fl 2 a week\nfor the baby\u2019s support. Cociia hgd Just\ngraduated from high school in Detroit\nwhen they eloped to Crown Point* \u00a3nd.,\non February 14, 1928.\nSilver is about the only ancient metal\nwhich has kept its pure state without\nalloy.\nWASHINGTON'S FINEST MEN\u2019S WEAR STORE\"\"\u2122\"\"\"\nRALEIGH HABERDASHER\n1319 F Street\nI\n1\nmm L\nTweed/\u2019 a\nTopcoat that can be\nused as a winter coat\n\nThis double-duty coat features the\nfamous Harris Tweeds...magnificant\nfabrics, made by hand in the islands\noff the northern coast of Scotland\nwhere the weaving of superior\ntweeds is a cottage industry dating\nback many years...fabrics that are\ndurable, warm without being bulky\nand woven in fresh new color mix\ntures...LlNED WITH TAN CASHMERE.\nif\n*SO\nfSoft \u2014pliant\ngenuine pigskin\nGLOVES\nThey\u2019re saddle-sewn and genuine\npigskin for longer wear. Their buff\nshade mellows as they grow older.\nAn exceptional value at $3.50.\n1\nOPPOSITE APPEALS\nMADE IN ELECTION\nHyde Recalls Lincoln\u2019s Ad\nvice, \u201cDon\u2019t Swap Horses\nin Middle of Stream.\u201d\ni\nBy the Associated Press.\nOpposed appeals to the Nation's alee\ntorate for a Democratic and Republican\nCongress were predicated last night by\ndivergent party spokesmen upon the\nsame subject\u2014economic conditions.\nSecretary Hyde, asking the re-election\nof Republican majorities in the House\nsnd Senate, emphasised the value of a\nloyal crew to aid President Hoover in\nbringing the ship of stite through a\nstorm of world-wide depression.\nSenator Swanson, Democrat, Virginia,\nblamed the administration for a farm\nrelief measure which he said depreciated\nthe price of farm products, and for the\nenactment of \u201conerous tariff rates'' and\nattendant \u201cdisastrous results.\"\nThe cabinet member recalled that \u201cin\nthe dark hours of the Civil War Abra\nham Lincoln stood for re-election upon\nthe slogan. \u2018Don\u2019t awap horses In the\nmiddle of the stream.\u201d\u2019\n\u201cToday I present the situation to my\nfellow citizens with the suggestion.\n\u2018Don\u2019t swap crews in the middle of the\nstorm,\u2019 he continued.\nAsserting that the main dependence\nof the Nation still wss placed in Presi\ndent Hoover, he asked if any good could\ncome from the election of those who\nwould be hostile by tradition and party\naffiliation.","height":"25413","width":"19683"}}
